I was born in Chelmsford in the autumn of 1979. It is now a city, though to our collective fury was not officially one at the time. It has a cathedral, and a river and a statue of Graham Gooch; it has a multistorey carpark, in which my mother parked one day on the roof, and never did it again no matter how many times I begged. It once had a number of beautiful Tudor streets flattened by a zealous local authority in the 60s; there are one or two sorry remnants, but nothing to admire.\
