I was a solitary girl, content to tread and re-tread the town, generally thinking of a novel I\'92d just read, or the ones I was intending to write when I was grown-up. So: Chelmsford made me, because I seldom went elsewhere, and if I did, it was generally with poor grace, and to other Essex towns.\
\
When I recall my youth, what I see is a series of buildings. There was the girls\'92 grammar school, a red brick building with parquet floors that seemed \'96 to a girl brought up in a 1973 semi \'96 rather grand and romantic. There would been precisely one famous school alumna, but she had been a TV presenter and died young, so it was difficult to feel any vicarious pride. There was the large and modern county library, which had to be accessed almost underground, where I indulged tastes \'96 Terry Pratchett! Stephen King! \'96 not to be found among the shelves of Austen and Hardy at home. When at the age of 16 I decided I\'92d outgrown my teachers, I began to play truant (when eventually suspended for this habit I felt not an ounce of contrition), taking my packed lunch to the library to read on the beanbags.\
\
