On the corner of New London Road there is a grey brick chapel, severely unadorned save for a single disc of coloured glass at the apex of each window, and it was here I was baptised and married and in the intervening years sang and recited scripture and thought about the condition of my immortal soul. As I write, other places sift up out of my memory: the little museum in which a stuffed bear roars at visitors from the foot of the stairs; the market stall where we bought six yards of oyster silk for my wedding dress; the cafe by the flour mill, where my parents took me for cheese toasties the day I passed my A-levels.\
\
I wanted out, of course: my family had been Londoners for generations back, and I was going to go there and be fascinating and wear a great deal of black. But I do not recall ever feeling anything for Chelmsford but a sort of offhand affection that has since warmed into pride. Recently I discovered an old Chelmsfordian called Anne Knight, born in 1786: a pioneer abolitionist and political radical, she wrote one of the earliest pamphlets on women\'92s suffrage. As an old woman she is shown grimly half-smiling in a photo, holding a sign that bids \'93the outraged world: BE FREE.\'94 I can\'92t see her shoes, but I bet they were stout. Now there\'92s an Essex girl.\
